  "prompt": "What universities for MS in CS should be considered with GRE - 317/340, CGPA - 9.15/10 and TOEFL - 102?",
  "response": "With a GRE score of 317, a CGPA of 9.15, and a TOEFL score of 102, you have a competitive profile for many reputable universities for a Master's in Computer Science. Here are some universities in the US and abroad that you may consider:\n\n### Top Tier Universities\n1. **University of California, Berkeley**\n2. **Stanford University**\n3. **Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)**\n4. **Carnegie Mellon University**\n5. **California Institute of Technology (Caltech)**\n\n### Highly Ranked Universities\n1. **University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign**\n2. **University of Michigan, Ann Arbor**\n3. **Georgia Institute of Technology**\n4. **University of Washington**\n5. **University of California, San Diego (UCSD)**\n\n### Good Universities with Strong Programs\n1. **University of California, Irvine**\n2. **University of Texas at Austin**\n3. **University of Wisconsin-Madison**\n4. **University of Southern California (USC)**\n5. **Northwestern University**\n\n### International Options\nIf you are considering studying abroad, you might also look into:\n1. **University of Oxford** (UK)\n2. **University of Cambridge** (UK)\n3. **Imperial College London** (UK)\n4. **ETH Zurich** (Switzerland)\n5. **National University of Singapore** (NUS)\n\n### Other Considerations\n- Research the faculty, specific programs, and research opportunities in your area of interest.\n- Consider the location, campus culture, and available funding or assistantships.\n- Make sure to check the application deadlines and specific admission requirements, as they can vary between institutions.\n\nYour scores give you a good chance at many of these programs, but remember that admissions decisions are also influenced by other factors like recommendation letters, statement of purpose, and relevant experience. Good luck with your applications!",
